HEADWORD: Pythoness
<hw>Pyth"o*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>pythonissa</ets>: cf. F. <ets>pythonisse</ets>. See
<er>Pythian</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Gr. Antiq.)</fld> <def>The
priestess who gave oracular answers at Delphi in Greece.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any woman supposed to have a spirit of divination; a
sort of witch.</def> <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pythonic</ent>⟦br⟧
